What is APR?APR stands for Annual Percentage Rate. It's a measure used to compare the yearly cost of borrowing or earning money across different loans, mortgages, credit cards, etc. The APR includes not only the interest rate but also any additional fees or costs associated with the transaction.

For example, if you're taking out a loan and the APR is 5%, that means your annual cost for borrowing this money (including all fees) will be equivalent to an interest rate of 5%. 

It's important to note that APR does not include compound interest. It provides a more comprehensive picture of the total cost of borrowing or earning over one year.

When shopping around for loans, mortgages, credit cards, etc., it's crucial to compare the APRs because this will give you an accurate idea of what each option costs in terms of annual expenses.yes

